Twelve specimens with regenerating anterior ends of the body were found in the examined material. Together they represent five consecutive stages of regeneration (
Fig. 7
). Different stages were recognized based on degree of development of regenerated part of the body, e.g. number of chaetigers and presence of chaetae.

Although posterior segment regeneration is very common among polychaetes (
Bely 2006
) we did not find specimens showing this state in our material.
